	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Pets, even in guard mode, only attack mobs that attack them or the mage that summoned them. Can understand where you got that idea from tho. Waaaaay back in EQ /pet guard used to make your pet attack any NPC that wandered by. You can imagine why they altered this. Poor lvl 4 mages getting reduced to a fine pink mist first time they hit /pet guard here in a town... As a very wise man once said, I pity da foo.<br><br>Actually pets have gotten a lot more acceptable on raids and groups lately. About the only time you run into trouble is when a mob goes running or gates and your pet chases after it. On the other hand there's an argument to be made that if in say, seb or karnors, you'd already be in trouble at that point from a train, so yer pet holding things up shouldn't hurt anything much.<br><br>But the most fundamental thing they changed was that pets no longer generate aggro unless they're attacking. So if your pet suddenly vanishes in hate or something, no, you're not dealing with a wipe. From that anyway. So yeah, there are arguments to be made for only summoning when ya need to, but it's a LOT safer now to have pets up than it was.<br><br><br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, the Mad Mage of Povar<br><br><br>(edit) PS: as to the original question I don't THINK it happens, but there are times when a chanter's been trying to mez and after the spell drops my pet is still attacking the mob it was on. It could be a few bugs in the system for automatically cancelling attack on mezzed mobs. Such as your pet being mid attack or something. Don't really know enough about mele to make a judgement. I will say this tho, if it happens, it doesn't happen often.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Feb 14 10:46:07 2003</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
