<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=10428386917930></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10428386917930><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=10428386917930>RE: specialisation</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=10428386917930#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73372><span id=Sage>Malaclypse</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>127 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 17th 4:53 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I will offer two answers to this question. I am offering two responses because the second one got a bit long. The first is this. No, there should be no major adverse effects.<br><br>Here is the second:<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;   Well, assuming that you're specializing in evocation, you may be better off just holding tight. See, here's the thing. Pre 50ish you're really almost better off with it in evoc. A little over half of the big nukes before 50 are evoc based, and under MOST circumstances (I'll get to the exception in a sec) you want your specialization to be what you're going to be nuking in.<br> <br>     Now, the big nukes for mages tend to alternate between evoc and conjure, scept for the ones past 57 or so. At that point they're pretty much even. 60+ you could argue either way based on nukes. The current last nuke we have at 65 is conjure based, however there are comparable spells of lower level based off of evoc. So if you're just talking nukes you can really go either way. Personally, I had spec:evoc maxed till I hit 53 or so, then I switched to conjure. However, at 55 I still find that I'm using evoc more, so I probably should have waited.<br><br>No, the place where conjuration really shines is with Pet Reclaiming. Now, I've yet to personally confirm this, but I've read a few posts ago that it's actually possible to regain mana by summoning a pet and reclaiming it over and over. This requires max specialization in conjure and hopefully an enshrouded veil or other summoning conservation item. I haven't gotten it to work for me yet, but there are other things that indicate that this would work, such as the improved reclaim ability, and the specialization improvements they offer. I seem to recall someone having parsed it somewhere to check, but it's been a while since I researched it.<br><br>The real reason for specializing in conjuration was pet reclaiming, chain petting, and God Rodding. Since they nerfed mod and god rods, some of the need for that has been removed.<br><br>To get back to your question, yeah, there's good reason to specialize in conjuration, but probably not before 50ish, when these tatics really become useful. (not to imply that chain petting isn't useful before 50, but you get the idea).<br><br>Once ya do switch though, it shouldn't cause any major problems. When I switched I really didn't notice that big of a difference. Either way, it's nothing game breaking. By the time you need to worry about it, evoc should be pretty solid even without the specialization backing it up.<br><br>To sum up. Specializing in evoc is nice, and it helps, and I'd reccomend it pre 50. Post 50 however, specialization in conjuration not only helps, but enables you to explore a whole bunch of new tatics that would otherwise be damn near impossible. Just my 2cp.<br><br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, the Mad Mage of Povar.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
